          "body": "Verse 10 delivers one of the most pointed dismissals in the dialogue: 'But come again, all of you now, for I do not find a wise man among you.' The invitation is sardonic — come back, try again, bring better arguments. Job's verdict is total: not one of the three, in all their speeches, has risen to the level of wisdom (*chakham*). This is not personal bitterness; it is a theological verdict that the book will ratify. When God speaks in chapters 38-41, He addresses Job, not the friends. When God's verdict is delivered in 42:7, He tells Eliphaz, 'you have not spoken of Me what is right, as My servant Job has.' Job's dismissal of the friends in 17:10 is, in retrospect, the accurate theological assessment the book ultimately endorses. The wise man the friends claim to be (cf. 15:9-10) and the wisdom they claim to offer are precisely what is absent from their counsel."
