        "excerpt": "Nevertheless the righteous will hold to his way, and he who has clean hands will grow stronger and stronger.",
        "body": "Verses 6-7 extend the documentation of Job's condition from the social to the physical. He has been made a *mashal* (byword, proverb, cautionary tale) by the people, a man at whom others spit (17:6). The cultural weight of this is enormous: in the ancient Near East, a person's reputation was inseparable from their honor, and to become a *mashal* was to be permanently inscribed in social memory as a negative example. Job was the greatest man of the east (1:3); now his name is the sentence other parents finish with 'and you don't want to end up like Job.' His eyes have grown dim from grief (*kaas* — vexation, bitter provocation) and his body is like a shadow — the physical substance of the man is wasting in real time.\n\nThen the chapter's most unexpected turn: verse 8 states that the upright (*yashar*) will be appalled at what has happened to Job, and the innocent will be stirred against the godless. The 'godless' (*chaneph*) in view are, by implication, the friends — men who profess piety but whose counsel exploits the suffering of the innocent. Job is claiming that his situation, seen clearly by genuinely righteous people, will produce righteous indignation against false accusers. This is not self-pity; it is a confidence that genuine integrity is recognizable to genuine integrity.\n\nVerse 9 delivers the chapter's most defiant affirmation: the righteous holds to his way, and the one with clean hands grows stronger and stronger. The verb *achaz* (holds to, grasps) implies an active, determined grip — not passive endurance but deliberate persistence. And *omets* (strength, moral firmness) is the quality that grows — not despite the trial but within it. This verse is the chapter's 'nevertheless' — the small but indestructible counter-note to the surrounding dissolution. Calvin rightly called this Job's clearest demonstration that genuine faith maintains its grip on integrity regardless of what circumstances announce about it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mashal* — proverb, taunt-song, cautionary example; the genre of Proverbs by the same root. *Chaneph* — the godless, the hypocrite; one who pollutes or profanes. *Achaz* — to grasp, to hold fast. *Omets* — strength, courage, firmness; the same root used of Joshua's call to 'be strong and courageous' (Joshua 1:6)."
